A fast bitcount macro for 32-bit integers uses a barrel shifter to count set bits in about 16 cycles/instructions on RISC machines, assuming 3 instructions/cycle is a lower bound. The key step is to shift and subtract the first column from the combined first and second columns. 

```c
int bitcount(int n) {
    int result = 0;
    while (n) {
        // shift and subtract the first column from the combined first and second columns
        n = (n & 0x55555555) + ((n >> 1) & 0x55555555);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        n = (n & 0x33333333) + ((n >> 2) & 0x33333333);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        n = (n & 0x0F0F0F0F0) + ((n >> 4) & 0x0F0F0F0F0);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        n = (n & 0xF0F0F0F0F) + ((n >> 8) & 0xF0F0F0F0F);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        n = (n & 0xFF00FF00) + ((n >> 16) & 0xFF00FF00);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        n = (n & 0xFFFF0000) + ((n >> 32) & 0xFFFF0000);
        result += n & 0x00000000;
        return result;
}
```

